flowRoot.flowPara: Using Graph Theory to Explore Organisational Changes During Retinal Development
Graph theory is the mathematical analysis of networks and provides a wide range of efficient metrics for understanding the organisation and dynamics of a network.
Graph theory is in heavy used in:
fMRI studies (macroscopic functional networks of neurons).
But has not been fully exploited in MEA or calcium imaging studies (microscopic functional networks).
A 2017 paper showed that a graph theoretic analysis identified changes in zebrafish tectum organisation that had been previously missed with other approaches.
Recently, other papers have also shown the benefit of graph theory in comparing wild-type vs. mutant groups and extracting neural assemblies.
Working with mathematicians & computer scientists will enable a new level of understanding through the study of 'neuronal graphs' - microscopic, functional networks of neurons.
Here we show how graph theory can quickly reproduce results previously aquired by MEAs.
